{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Phase 1: Data Exploration (EDA)\n",
    "\n",
    "In this notebook, we will load our raw Amazon reviews dataset and perform exploratory data analysis to understand the distribution of sentiments, review lengths, and basic statistics. This is a crucial step before moving to feature engineering."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set plotting style\n",
    "sns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\")\n",
    "plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (10, 6)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Load the Data\n",
    "First, let's load the dataset. If you haven't generated the mock data yet, run `python src/generate_mock_data.py` from the project root."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "try:\n",
    "    df = pd.read_csv('../data/raw_reviews.csv')\n",
    "    print(f\"Successfully loaded {len(df)} reviews.\")\n",
    "except FileNotFoundError:\n",
    "    print(\"Error: data/raw_reviews.csv not found. Please run the mock data generator script first.\")\n",
    "    df = pd.DataFrame() # Create empty dataframe so subsequent cells don't hard crash"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Preview the data\n",
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    display(df.head())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Basic Statistics and Data Types"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    print(\"Data info:\")\n",
    "    df.info()\n",
    "    print(\"\\nMissing values:\")\n",
    "    print(df.isnull().sum())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Rating Distribution\n",
    "Let's see how our ratings are distributed. We typically consider 4-5 stars as positive, 1-2 stars as negative, and 3 stars as neutral."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\n",
    "    sns.countplot(x='rating', data=df, palette='viridis')\n",
    "    plt.title('Distribution of Review Ratings')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Rating (Stars)')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Count')\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Define Sentiment Labels\n",
    "For our binary classification models (Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, LSTM), we will drop 3-star reviews (or group them, but dropping is standard for clear polarity) and map 4-5 to `1` (Positive) and 1-2 to `0` (Negative)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    # Remove 3-star reviews for binary classification\n",
    "    df_binary = df[df['rating'] != 3].copy()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Create binary label\n",
    "    df_binary['sentiment'] = df_binary['rating'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x > 3 else 0)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(f\"Rows after removing 3-star reviews: {len(df_binary)}\")\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
    "    sns.countplot(x='sentiment', data=df_binary, palette='Set2')\n",
    "    plt.title('Sentiment Distribution (0=Negative, 1=Positive)')\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5. Review Length Analysis\n",
    "Let's check if there's a difference in length between positive and negative reviews."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    df_binary['text_length'] = df_binary['text'].apply(lambda x: len(str(x)))\n",
    "    df_binary['word_count'] = df_binary['text'].apply(lambda x: len(str(x).split()))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    sns.boxplot(x='sentiment', y='word_count', data=df_binary, ax=axes[0], palette='Set2')\n",
    "    axes[0].set_title('Word Count by Sentiment')\n",
    "    \n",
    "    sns.histplot(data=df_binary, x='word_count', hue='sentiment', bins=50, kde=True, ax=axes[1], palette='Set2')\n",
    "    axes[1].set_title('Word Count Distribution')\n",
    "    axes[1].set_xlim(0, 100) # Limit x-axis if there are extreme outliers\n",
    "    \n",
    "    plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "    plt.show()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    print(\"Average word count by sentiment:\")\n",
    "    display(df_binary.groupby('sentiment')['word_count'].mean())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6. Save Processed Labels\n",
    "We will save this labeled dataset for Phase 2 (Preprocessing & Feature Engineering)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "if not df.empty:\n",
    "    output_path = '../data/labeled_reviews.csv'\n",
    "    # Keep only what we need\n",
    "    final_df = df_binary[['review_id', 'text', 'sentiment']]\n",
    "    final_df.to_csv(output_path, index=False)\n",
    "    print(f\"Saved {len(final_df)} labeled reviews to {output_path}\")"
   ]
  }
 ],
